{{Infobox stadium | image = [[File:Big Hat 02.jpg|280px|Makomanai Indoor Stadium]]| stadium_name = Nagano Wakasato Tamokuteki Sports Arena| location = [[Nagano, Nagano|Nagano]], [[Japan]] | broke_ground =| closed =| demolished =| owner = Nagano City| operator = M-Wave Co.| construction_cost =| architect =| opened = 10 December 1995| surface = | tenants = | seating_capacity = 10,104| }}
{{nihongo|'''The Big Hat'''|ビッグハット|Biggu Hatto}} is an indoor [[ice hockey]] [[arena]] in [[Nagano, Nagano|Nagano]], [[Japan]] with a capacity of 10,104 seated spectators. Its official name is the '''''Nagano Wakasato Tamokuteki Sports Arena'''''. The arena was completed and officially opened on December 10, 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shinmai.co.jp/feature/oly-eng/kaijo/bighat.htm|title=Ice Hockey Stadium|publisher=Shinmai Mainchi Newspaper|language=English|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>
The [[Ice hockey at the 1998 Winter Olympics|ice hockey]] games from the [[1998 Winter Olympics]], including the men's and women's finals, were held at this arena. The rink still serves as the location of the [[Nagano Cup]], an annual ice hockey tournament held to commemorate the 1998 games, as well as many [[short track speed skating]] competitions. The Wakasato hall in the complex features a stage and theater seating, and frequently serves as a venue for music recitals and public meetings. [[File:Big Hat.png|thumb|left|300px|Satellite view]] ==References== {{reflist}}
